properties.title: All eyes on South Africa at the MOMA
properties.description: Hoosta Magazine posted a photo: From the Apartheid to the dawn of democracy, the exhibition Impressions from South Africa, 1965 to now goes back on the artistic evolution of South Africa, through unprecedented turbulent times. The New York Museum Of Modern Art presents over a hundred works, posters, books and wall stencils from over 30 artists, showing the extraordinary scope and impact of printmaking in South Africa. A striking example of art fighting for survival. “Impressions from South Africa, 1965 to now” exhibition until August 14th 2011 at the New York Museum of Modern Art. Open from Saturday to Thursday from 10.30 am to 5.30 pm and on Fridays until 8 pm. Closed on Tuesdays. Check out Hôtel du Jeu de Paume ! Check out Hôtel du Jeu de Paume ! Hôtel du Jeu de Paume, member of Hoosta Luxury Hotels Collection.Go to his page on Hoosta. The Museum of Modern Art 11 West 53 Street New-York, NY 10019 USA

properties.title: Visions of New York: Crown Heights
properties.description: Stephen*Iliffe posted a photo: During our tour of Brooklyn, our mini-bus drove through Crown Heights, an extraordinary community where on one side lives the orthodox Jewish community, and on the other side Afro-Americans. It happened to be a Jewish holy day, and Ben and I saw dozens of families returning from the synagogue, with the men wearing huge round 'shteimel' hats, made from mink fur, and trailing long black coats,. As this family strolled past graffiti-covered walls, they seemed proud and confident in their ancient tradition, and seemingly unfazed by the 21st century. No.7 in a series of impressions of New York

properties.title: Ben and Jerome 'JDL' Wilson
properties.description: Stephen*Iliffe posted a photo: Today we went on the Brooklyn Hip Hop Tour led by one of the original artists from the scene - Jerome JDL Wilson, a member of the Cold Crush Brothers. Jerome was a wonderful guide and told us all about the history, sociology and culture of Brooklyn and the Hip Hop scene as well having lots of good stories to share. Here, Ben and JDL pose outside the house where the famous Hip Hop artist Biggie Smalls was raised. Crown Heights, Brooklyn, New York.www.hushhiphoptours.com
